John Edward: Language skills are fundamental to the citizens of the world
Independent schools in Scotland have a track record of academic excellence that has continued in 2018 with another set of extraordinary results in exams that is reinforced by individual and collective successes in the fields of sport, art, music and other community projects.
With over 30,000 pupils across Scotland, these centres, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Colleges (SCIS), strive to deliver the best level of service to pupils and parents.
Independent schools are designed to prepare students for further education, for their chosen career and for their place as world citizens.
As an education sector that can design and implement an adapted curriculum, modern languages remain a popular and desirable subject in schools.
As Nelson Mandela said, "If you speak to a man in a language he understands, the message reaches his head.
If you speak to him in his language, it reaches his heart.
This is a powerful reminder that if you want to build relationships and build trust with people from other countries, you cannot rely solely on English.
If we take into account the recent results of this year's exams, we can see that languages are at the top of the rankings, with the highest pass rates in independent schools.
In total, 68% of students who studied foreign languages got an A, the highest grade.
Data from the 74 centres that are part of the SCIS showed that 72% of students obtained an A in Mandarin, while 72% of those studying German, 69% of those studying French and 63% of those studying Spanish also obtained an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as they consider them a fundamental competence that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Currently, languages are considered to be at the same level as the CTIM (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) subjects in the curricula of independent schools and everywhere.
A survey carried out in 2014 by the UK's Employment and Skills Commission revealed that 17% of the reasons given by employers for the difficulties they encountered in filling jobs were attributed to a lack of language skills.
Language skills are therefore increasingly essential to prepare young people for their future careers.
The potential for job opportunities that require languages are increasing, so these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career you choose, if you have learned a second language, you will have a real advantage in the future thanks to a competition like this, which will last a lifetime.
The fact that they can communicate directly with people from foreign countries will allow that person to automatically outperform the competition.
According to a survey by YouGov of over 4,000 UK adults in 2013, 75% of them spoke no foreign language well enough to have a conversation.
For this reason, investing in language teaching is now important for today's children.
If children know several languages, especially those of developing economies, they will be equipped to have better opportunities to find quality employment.
In Scotland, each school will teach different languages.
Some centres will focus on the more classical modern languages, while others will teach the languages considered most important for the UK towards 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever the child's interests, in independent schools you can always choose between several languages taught by specialist teachers.
Independent schools in Scotland are dedicated to providing a learning environment that prepares children and equipps them with the skills they need to succeed, whatever the future may bring.
At present, it is undeniable that, in a global business environment, languages continue to have vital importance for the future of the country, so this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages must be considered competencies for international communication.
Independent schools will continue to offer these options, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
It's got to be done right.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Colleges
