The application uses Solid technology so users can create their own "online personal data storage" or POD.
It may contain lists, to-do lists, calendar, music library and other personal and professional tools.
It's like Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify are all available in one browser and at the same time.
Something that is unique about online personal data storage is that the user is the one who completely decides who can access what kind of information.
The company calls it "personal training through data".
The idea of Inrupt, according to the company's CEO, John Bruce, is to incorporate the resources, processes and skills needed so Solid can reach everyone.
At the moment, the company is made up of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform that IBM bought, some of the developers included in the template who were hired to work on the project, and a community of volunteer programmers.
