The new German warship, postponed again
The new German Navy frigate should have been commissioned in 2014 to replace the old Cold War-era ships, but it won't be until at least next year due to faulty systems and the progressive increase in costs, local media reported.
The delivery of the "Rheinland-Pfalz", the ship leading the new Baden-Württemberg-class frigates, has now been postponed until the first half of 2019, according to a statement by a military spokesman.
The ship was supposed to join the Navy in 2014, but the problems that arose after delivery derailed the completion of the ambitious project.
The four Baden-Wuerttemberg-class ships ordered by the Navy in 2007 will replace the old Bremen-class frigates.
We know they will include a powerful cannon, a set of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles, as well as some invisibility technologies, such as radar, infrared and very low-resonance acoustics.
Other important features include longer maintenance periods, so that they can be deployed up to two years away from the ports of origin.
However, the continuing delays have caused the innovative ships (which were supposed to allow Germany to project its power overseas) to be outdated by the time they start service, Die Zeit points out.
The unfortunate F125 frigate made headlines last year when the German Navy officially refused to put the ship into service and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
It's the first time the Navy has returned a ship to a shipyard after it was delivered.
Little was known about the reasons behind the return, but German media cited a number of crucial "software and hardware flaws" that left the ship virtually useless if sent on a combat mission.
The software deficiencies were particularly significant, as the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class ships will be operated by a crew of about 120 sailors - half the staff of the former Bremen-class frigates.
It was also found that the vessel is overweight, which reduces its performance and limits the Navy's ability to add future upgrades.
The 7,000-ton Rheinland-Pfalz is believed to be twice as heavy as other similar-class ships used by the Germans in World War II.
In addition to the faulty hardware, the price of the entire project, including crew training, has also been a problem.
It is believed to have reached €3.1 billion ($36 billion), instead of the initial €2.2 billion.
The problems associated with the new frigates are of particular relevance in the light of recent warnings about the reduction of Germany's naval power.
Earlier this year, Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the German parliament's defence committee, acknowledged that the Navy is "leaving without ships capable of deployment".
The officer said the problem has been getting worse over time, because old ships were taken out of service, but not replaced by others.
He regretted that none of the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class frigates had been able to join the Navy.
The National Trust spies on the secret life of bats
This new research, which has been conducted in a Scottish Highlands state, tries to discover how bats use the landscape in their search for food.
Everything that is discovered is expected to shed more light on the behaviour of the only flying mammals and help guide future conservation activities.
The study, conducted by the National Trust for Scotland, will follow common bats and sopranos as well as the Daubenton Riverhead bats and long-eared browns from the Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed in strategic locations on the property to track bat activities during the season.
The NHS staff and volunteers will also carry out mobile research with portable detectors.
Experts will analyze the sounds recorded to find out how often bats call and what species do.
A report and a habitat map will then be produced to create a detailed picture of the environment and its behaviour.
Rob Dewar, nature conservation advisor for NTS, hopes the results will reveal which areas of habitat are most important to bats and how each species uses them.
This information will determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as the creation of meadows and how forests should be maintained for bats and other associated species.
Bat populations in Scotland and the UK have declined considerably over the last century.
They are threatened by the construction and development of their nests and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and electrical wiring can also pose a risk to them, as can insecticidal paper and other chemical treatments of building materials or attacks by domestic cats.
Bats aren't really blind,
But because of their nighttime hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes in achieving their target.
They use a sophisticated ecolocation technique that locates ants and obstacles in their flight path.
The NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, takes the bat issue very seriously.
It has ten trained experts in the field, who regularly carry out surveys, nest inspections and, occasionally, rescue operations.
The organisation has even opened Scotland's first and only bat reserve in the Threave state in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
The property manager, David Thompson, says it's the ideal territory for them.
"Here, in Threave, we have a fantastic bat zone", he said.
"We have old buildings, many veteran trees and all the right habitat.
However, there is still much unknown about bats, so the work we do here and in other properties will help us better understand what they need to develop".
It stresses the importance of checking for bats before carrying out maintenance tasks within the properties, as a breeding colony can be unintentionally destroyed and 400 females and young could be killed, which would mean the annihilation of an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, harass or disturb them, as well as destroy their colonies.
Elisabeth Ferrell, the Scottish officer in charge of the Bat Conservation Trust, has encouraged the public to collaborate.
He said: "We still have a lot to learn about bats and many other species about which we don't know how their populations evolve".
