Red tide update: Reducing concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The new report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows a general reduction in red tide concentrations in Tampa Bay area areas.
According to the FWC, irregular flowering conditions are being reported in areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties, suggesting a reduction in concentrations.
The red tide bloom extends approximately 130 miles of coastline from Pinellas County in the north to Lee County in the south.
Irregular plots can be found about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but in fewer places compared to last week.
Red tide has also been detected in Pasco County.
During the past week, mean concentrations in Pinellas County and its coastline, low-to-high concentrations on the coastline of Hillsborough County, bottom-to-high concentrations in Manatee County, bottom-to-high concentrations in Sarasota County and its coastline, bottom-to-medium concentrations in Charlotte County, bottom-to-high concentrations in Lee County and its coastline, and low concentrations in Collier County have been reported.
Respiratory irritation problems are still reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
No respiratory irritation problems have been reported in the northwest Florida area during the past week.
